The '''New York Entomological Society''' was founded in 1892.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Leng|first1=Charles W.|title=History of the New York Entomological Society, 1893-1918|journal=Journal of the New York Entomological Society|date=1918|volume=26|issue=3/4|pages=129–133|jstor=25003813}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Klots|first1=Elsie B.|title=The History of the New York Entomological Society|journal=Journal of the New York Entomological Society|date=1968|volume=76|issue=3|pages=138–155|jstor=25006114}}</ref> The '''Brooklyn Entomological Society''' merged with the Society in 1968.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Announcement of Consolidation|journal=Journal of the New York Entomological Society|date=1968|volume=76|issue=3|pages=136–137|jstor=25006113}}</ref> The Society publishes ''[[Entomologica Americana (New York Entomological Society)|Entomologica Americana]]'' which is the successor to the ''[[Journal of the New York Entomological Society]]''.
A related society, the '''New York Entomological Club''', briefly existed between 1880 and 1882. It published the first two volumes of ''[[Papilio (New York Entomological Club)|Papilio]]'', a journal entirely devoted to [[Lepidoptera]], during the years 1881 and 1882. After the society's activities ceased, two more volumes of ''Papilio'' were published between 1883 and 1884, after which the journal ceased publication.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Weiss|first1=Harry B.|title=The New York Entomological Club and "Papilio"|journal=Journal of the New York Entomological Society|date=1948|volume=56|issue=2|pages=119–136|jstor=25005259}}</ref>
