{{unreferenced|date=October 2015}}
'''Phyletic dwarfism''' is the decrease in average size of animals of a species. There are a few circumstances that often lead to species doing this. Lack of [[Predation|predators]] of smaller creatures can allow smaller members of a species to survive. The lack of resources to sustain a large population of larger animals can pick off the largest specimens. Available resources being more beneficial for smaller creatures can also do so.
These circumstances are common on islands, making [[insular dwarfism]] the most common form of phyletic dwarfism. Examples of this are the [[Island fox|Channel Island fox]], extinct [[dwarf elephant]]s of Crete, and ''[[Brookesia micra]]'', a minuscule chameleon from Madagascar. An noninsular example is the evolution of dwarfed [[Callitrichidae|marmosets and tamarins]] among New World monkeys.<ref name="Perelman">{{Cite journal | last1= Perelman |first1= P. | year = 2011 | title = A Molecular Phylogeny of Living Primates | journal = PLOS Genetics | volume = 7 | issue = 3 | pages = 1–17 | doi=10.1371/journal.pgen.1001342| url=http://www.plosgenetics.org/article/info:doi/10.1371/journal.pgen.1001342 | pmid=21436896 | pmc=3060065|display-authors=etal}}</ref> Phyletic dwarfism may have also helped give rise to birds from their much larger dinosaur ancestors.
